# qa_2025_08_20
This repo contains a Q&amp;A file and relevant examples

**How to maximize premium requests?** 

* *You donâ€™t need to use premium requests for everything.*   
* *Use Ask mode \+ GPT models for questions; similar to how people use Chat GPT.*   
* *Use Edit mode \+ GPT models for when you have a clear understanding of the specific changes you want in a file.*   
* *Use Agent mode \+ Sonnet 4 or GPT 5 for more complex, multi-step tasks that you want the agent to autonomously complete.*   
* *When giving Agent mode \+ Sonnet 4 or GPT 5 a task, be sure to give it complete requirements from the start. If you give it incomplete requirements and you ask it to modify the output, an additional premium request will be consumed.*   
* *Read about more tips [here](https://gist.github.com/xrvk/5d5b4e2e1e049bba6222202f5a6b4ec6#how-to-maximize-your-usage-and-avoid-limits) and [here](https://github.blog/ai-and-ml/github-copilot/agent-mode-101-all-about-github-copilots-powerful-mode/).* 

**What are the best premium models for Agent mode right now?** 

* *Sonnet 4 is known to be the best model.*   
* *We are seeing that GPT 5 will follow prompt files and custom instructions with higher precision. If this is a concern with Sonnet 4, you should consider GPT 5\.* 

**How do I track my premium request usage?** 

* [*Click the Copilot icon in your IDE*](https://docs.github.com/en/copilot/how-tos/manage-and-track-spending/monitor-premium-requests#viewing-usage-in-your-ide) *![][image1]*   
* *In Visual Studio Code, click the Copilot icon in the status bar on the lower right corner.*   
* *In Visual Studio, click the Copilot icon in the top right corner, then click Copilot Consumptions.*   
* *In JetBrains IDEs, click the Copilot icon in the status bar on the lower right corner, then select View quote usage.*   
* *In Xcode, click the Copilot icon in the menu bar.*   
* *In Eclipse, click the Copilot icon in the status bar at the bottom of Eclipse.* 

**When do you use prompt file vs. instructions file?** 

* *Prompt files:*    
* *To define reusable, task-specific prompts that can be executed directly in Copilot Chat. They encapsulate specific instructions and context for a particular task. Creating reusable prompts for common coding tasks, such as generating specific components (e.g., React forms, API mocks), writing tests, or handling migrations.*   
* *Here is [an example](https://github.com/vishaljsoni/octocat-supply-chain-demo/blob/main/.github/prompts/demo-unit-test-coverage.prompt.md) in a sample project.*   
* *Read more about this [here](https://code.visualstudio.com/docs/copilot/customization/prompt-files).*   
* *Custom instructions:*    
* *To provide project-wide or team-specific context and guidelines to GitHub Copilot. These files act as a system prompt, influencing all interactions with Copilot within that repository. Defining coding standards, preferred frameworks, and project-specific conventions.*   
* *Here is [an example](https://github.com/vishaljsoni/octocat-supply-chain-demo/blob/main/.github/copilot-instructions.md) in a sample project.*   
* *Read more about this [here](https://docs.github.com/en/copilot/how-tos/configure-custom-instructions/add-repository-instructions).*   
* *Checkout [this blog](https://github.blog/ai-and-ml/github-copilot/copilot-ask-edit-and-agent-modes-what-they-do-and-when-to-use-them/) if you need more guidance.* 

**Can I use more than one custom instructions file in a repository?** 

* Yes. When you do this you must provide an applyTo formatter to the file. This will allow you to specify which directory and files in the repository to apply the instructions to.   
* Read more [here](https://docs.github.com/en/copilot/how-tos/configure-custom-instructions/add-repository-instructions#using-one-or-more-instructionsmd-files-1).  

**How do I know if a model will consume a premium request?** 

* *When you select the model to use in Copilot Chat, the number of premium requests that apply will be indicated to the right of the model name.*

**Can you point to more than one repository in your context?** 

* *Yes. If you open a directory in your IDE that contains more than one repository codebase, all repositories can be used in the context as long as indexing is complete. To ensure local indexing is completed [read more here](https://code.visualstudio.com/docs/copilot/reference/workspace-context#_local-index).*   
* *Select files and folders you want to focus on in the context, or us the \#path and \#file variables to specify files and folders to focus on.*   
* *Read more about slash commands and variables [here](https://docs.github.com/en/enterprise-cloud@latest/copilot/reference/cheat-sheet?tool=vscode).* 

 

**If our frontend code is in one repository and backend is in another repository, how can we ensure Copilot has what it needs from the backend repository?** 

* *See the question above for a potential solution.*   
* *Consider using a prompt file to generate a markdown file for backend resources that are intended to be consumed by the frontend codebase. In the prompt file ask Copilot to include request body examples, authentication and authorization requirements, as well as sample response for each endpoint. Then reference the markdown file in your prompts or custom instructions.* 

**How can we include custom built libraries in Copilot context?** 

* *Consider using a prompt file to generate a markdown file for the libraries. In the prompt file ask Copilot to provide required arguments, argument type, returns and return type for all methods and classes. Then reference the markdown file in your prompts or custom instructions.* 

**How can we provide Copilot with internal API guidelines?** 

* *Consider storing markdown file with guidelines in the repository. You can generate this file using the Copilot. Be sure to explicitly tell Copilot to include authentication, authorization, error handling, caching, pagination, documentation requirements, etc.* 

**How can we make documentation available to all developers across different teams?** 

* *With your current setup, the best approach is to include markdown files containing the required documentation in all repositories and reference those markdown files in custom instructions and prompt files. You can leverage Copilot to generate these markdown files.*
